\begin_layout Subsection
Symmetric spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This and the next two sections flesh out the details of an idea presented
 by Harland
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Harland16"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 be a compact connected Lie group.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha:G\to G$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(gg^{\prime}\right)=\alpha\left(g\right)\alpha\left(g^{\prime}\right)$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}\left(g\right)=\alpha\left(\alpha\left(g\right)\right)=g$
\end_inset

.
 This is the definition of an involution.
 The fixed points 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in G$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 are by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(h\right)=h$
\end_inset

.
 These form a subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H\subset G$
\end_inset

 and the quotient space 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is a symmetric space – by defintion, symmetric spaces are quotients of
 a group by it's involution-invariant subgroup.
 It's assumed that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is non-trivial, 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a proper subgroup that 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is not the trivial subgroup.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This function 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as a permutation of two 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

parts
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

; the subgroup 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is then the diagonal of a product of these two parts.
 Later on, these will be identified as the left and right chiral pieces
 of the sigma model; there is no need to do this, yet, and so the following
 proceeds in a generic fashion.
 (There are actually three possibilities: 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a real simple Lie group, or 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the product of two compact simple Lie groups (this is the conventional
 sigma model) or 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the complexification of a compact simple Lie group, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 is non-compact, and 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the maximal compact subgroup of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 be the corresponding Lie algbera of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 descends to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 the identity, it's eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm1$
\end_inset

.
 It splits 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 into odd and even subspaces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}=\mathfrak{m}\oplus\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

.
 The odd-parity subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 can be identified as the tangent space of 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 at the identity and the even-parity subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 is the Lie algebra of 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathfrak{h},\mathfrak{h}\right]\subseteq\mathfrak{h}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad\left[\mathfrak{m},\mathfrak{h}\right]\subseteq\mathfrak{m}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad\left[\mathfrak{m},\mathfrak{m}\right]\mathfrak{\subseteq h}
\]

\end_inset

The easiest way to see this is to note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left[X,Y\right]=\left[\alpha\left(X\right),\alpha\left(Y\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $X,Y\in\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $X=X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}$
\end_inset

 and note the 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\left(X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}\right)=\left(-X_{\mathfrak{m}}\right)\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then clearly the parity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus0,0\oplus Y_{\mathfrak{h}}\right]$
\end_inset

 is negative, while the parity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0\oplus X_{\mathfrak{h}},0\oplus Y_{\mathfrak{h}}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[X_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus0,Y_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus0\right]$
\end_inset

 is positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two more identities will be useful.
 The adjoint action 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ad}_{g}X=gXg^{-1}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

 behaves as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha\left(\mbox{Ad}_{g}X\right)=\alpha\left(gXg^{-1}\right)=\alpha\left(g\right)\alpha\left(X\right)\alpha\left(g^{-1}\right)=\mbox{Ad}_{\alpha\left(g\right)}\alpha\left(X\right)
\]

\end_inset

Given a curve 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma:\mathbb{R}\to G$
\end_inset

 on the group manifold, the tangent vector 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\gamma^{-1}\partial_{t}\gamma$
\end_inset

 to the curve transforms as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha\left(\gamma^{-1}\partial_{t}\gamma\right)=\alpha\left(\gamma^{-1}\right)\partial_{t}\alpha\left(\gamma\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's belabor the obvious; this will be useful a bit later.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a Lie group, the tangent space 
\begin_inset Formula $TG$
\end_inset

 has a natural coordinate system given by the adjoint map.
 That is, given a point 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in G$
\end_inset

 and a basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\in\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

, the corresponding basis at point 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Ad}_{g}e_{i}=ge_{i}g^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 This basis splits into two parts, given by lifting the projections the
 projections 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathfrak{h}}:\mathfrak{g}\to\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}:\mathfrak{g}\to\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 to all of 
\begin_inset Formula $TG$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Maurer-Cartan form
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Cartan form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is a one-form on 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 given by the differential 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{g^{-1}}$
\end_inset

 and specifically, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{g}=L_{g^{-1}*}$
\end_inset

 The definition of the differential is given in Bleeker section 0.2.5 page
 8.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is embeded in 
\begin_inset Formula $GL(n)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{g}=g^{-1}dg$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
i.e.

\emph default
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

left logarithmic derivative of the identity map of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 to be a principle bundle over a single point, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the principle connection on that bundle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a homogenous space 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

 and a section 
\begin_inset Formula $s:G/H\to G$
\end_inset

 then the pullback 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=s^{*}\omega$
\end_inset

 transforms in the appropriate gauge-like way, and has a vanishing curvature.
 See Wikipedia 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Maurer–Cartan form
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This pullback can be decomposed as 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\left(\theta\right)\oplus\pi_{\mathfrak{h}}\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is apparently an equivalent characterization where a metric is provided
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

, which is then decomposed into vielbeins
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Yilmaz07"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The rest of that article appears to deal with the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is non-compact, which appears to be the case of interest for supergravity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vector and Gauge fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of this section is to set up the basic ingredients for the sigma
 model as the dynamics of a field 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, the sigma field, valued in the symmetric space 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H$
\end_inset

.
 This is not the conventional construction but close to it.
 The end goal of the construction is to define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{\mu}=\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\circ\left(g^{-1}\partial_{\mu}g\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}:\mathfrak{g}\to\mathfrak{m}$
\end_inset

 is the projection above, and then use this in the Skyrme Lagrangian.
 This is well and fine, but practical calculations require the idea to be
 articulated.
 I'll try to do this carefully, to avoid later confusion due to glibness.
 This necessitates a dive back to first principles and basic (textbook)
 definitions (The textbook being Bleecker).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P\to M$
\end_inset

 be a smooth principal fiber bundle (PFB) over a smooth manifold 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with structure group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P$
\end_inset

 be a point above 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{x}$
\end_inset

 is diffeomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in M$
\end_inset

.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in P$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 acting on the right, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $p\mapsto pg$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{g}:P\to P$
\end_inset

 for this right-action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset M$
\end_inset

, a connection is a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

-valued 1-form 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 that is covariant under gauge transformations.
 For the present purposes, a gauge transformation is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $g:U\to G$
\end_inset

 and the connection transforms as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega\mapsto g^{-1}\omega g+g^{-1}dg
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Earlier, 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 was split into 
\begin_inset Formula $G/H\times H$
\end_inset

 and correspondingly, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}=\mathfrak{m}\oplus\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

 and this split can be applied to the connection.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{g}$
\end_inset

-valued, write 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\left(\omega\right)\oplus\pi_{\mathfrak{h}}\left(\omega\right)=\omega_{\mathfrak{m}}\oplus\omega_{\mathfrak{h}}$
\end_inset

.
 Under gauge transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $h\in H$
\end_inset

, one has that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\left(\omega\right)\mapsto\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\left(h^{-1}\omega h+h^{-1}dh\right)=h^{-1}\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\left(\omega\right)h
\]

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}dh$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{h}$
\end_inset

-valued 1-form, and thus projected out (that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{\mathfrak{m}}\left(\mathfrak{h}\right)=0$
